        { philosopher: 'Lewis White Beck', text: 'Beck\'s Early German Philosophy (1969) and his Early Kant essays placed the Inaugural Dissertation in its proper context: the culmination of Kant\'s pre-critical development and the starting gun of his critical transformation. Beck articulated the gap between the Dissertation and the first Critique with characteristic precision: Kant saw in 1770 that sensibility has its own a priori forms; he did not yet see that the intellect is equally limited. The decade of silence is the decade in which this second insight was won — the insight that the categories of the understanding, which the Dissertation treats as giving us access to things in themselves, are in fact valid only within the domain of experience constituted by sensibility.' }
