        { philosopher: 'Robert Louden', text: 'Louden\'s Kant\'s Impure Ethics (2000) is the most sustained argument for taking the Anthropology seriously as a contribution to Kant\'s moral philosophy. Louden argued that the standard picture of Kantian ethics as purely formal and a priori — concerned only with the categorical imperative and its applications — is a distortion created by focusing exclusively on the Groundwork and the second Critique. The Anthropology provides the empirical dimension of Kant\'s ethics: the detailed knowledge of human nature, human motivation, human weakness, and human social interaction that any realistic moral philosophy must engage with. Without the Anthropology, Kantian ethics floats free of the human beings it is supposed to govern; with it, it becomes a practical philosophy adequate to actual moral life.' },
        { philosopher: 'Patrick Frierson', text: 'Frierson\'s Freedom and Anthropology in Kant\'s Moral Philosophy (2003) showed that the Anthropology is indispensable for understanding Kant\'s moral psychology — his account of how moral agency operates in beings like us, who are simultaneously rational and animal, free and determined, capable of moral transformation and prone to self-deception. The Anthropology\'s treatment of the passions, the temperaments, and the mechanisms of self-deception provides the empirical content that the categorical imperative must engage with in practice. Kant\'s ethics is not merely formal — it is applied to the complex, self-deceiving, passion-driven creatures that human beings actually are, and the Anthropology is where this application is worked out.' }
